entry.title: [Uno-d] Add helper function `IsImplicitBrowserSigninOrExplicitDisabled`
entry.content:
`IsImplicitBrowserSigninOrExplicitDisabled()` will be used to disntguish

Dice users with the feature off or on but they were implicitly signed

in, therefore they might be subject to pre-Explicit browser sign in

behavior.



The function will return true:

- If the explicit browser sign in is disabled

- or the user is signed in implicitly.

Otherwise, returns false when the feature is off and the user is either

signed out or signed in explicitly. In this case, explicit browser sign

in fully applies.

entry.content:

in Setup after context. During Teardown the context gets reset before

removing the whole Teardown as test suite should automatically handle

it in destructor.



Also add ClearMappedBufferMap and ClearMappedTextureMap in Gles2Impl

which frees shared memory and clear maps in case appropriate Unmaps

are not called. This is more as a precautionary measure.

entry.title: [Topics] Measure a misuse pattern: topics called on a page after redirects
entry.content:
What: When Topics API is first invoked in a page, record 1) the

number of automated client-side redirect occurred before this page,

and 2) among those redirects, the number of pages that invoked

Topics API.



Why: Topics API can be misused when a site gets topics and passes

it to the next site in the URL param via automated redirect, and

repeating this process several times allows the cooperating sites

to get all the user's topics upon a single page visit (i.e. 3 topics

per site, and 15 topics from 5 sites). Thus, we want to better

understand the usage patterns.



How: Add a WebContentsObserver that tracks the topics usage in a

chain of automated redirects, by getting the previous page's redirect

status, updating it, and initializing the next page with the updated

status. When Topics API is first used in a page, record UMA metrics.

See the class comment for `BrowsingTopicsRedirectObserver` for

details.

disabled. End users are not supposed to experience that, the feature

is launched. This is one more step towards cleaning up the flag.

standalone sync consent screen (/user_signin/). After this CL, the

entry.title: [anchor] Support try-tactic flips for self-alignment properties
entry.content:
The self-alignment properties are a bit different from the other

properties that require adjustment.



For insets and sizes, a value transformation (e.g. anchor(right)

becoming anchor(left)) is always accompanied by a corresponding property

transformation (e.g. left becoming right), but for self-alignment

properties we need value transformation within the same property.

E.g. justify-self:start under flip-start becomes justify-self:end

(no change in property). Therefore these properties are always present

in the try-tactics layer.



Also, it's worth noting that justify-self accepts the 'left' and

'right' keywords, but align-self does not accept 'top'/'bottom'.

This means we can't just naively grab-and-flip the value of the other

property for flip-start: we need to convert left/right to logical

to avoid giving align-self an invalid value. Since the exact details

of what left/right should become in this case is non-obvious

(and not specified) [1], I've avoided this case in the WPT for now.



Bug: 40279608



[1] https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/issues/10049

entry.title: [PIX] Pass RenderFrameHost to the facilitated payments API client
entry.content:
This patch passes a RenderFrameHost into the

FacilitatedPaymentsApiClient, so it can be used to retrieve the Android

context to invoke Android APIs in the 1p implementation. The

RenderFrameHost is passed instead of Context, because the Context can be

an Activity, which can change, e.g., when a user selects "Open in

Chrome" from a Chrome Custom Tab (CCT) menu.



In order to pass to the RenderFrameHost, the factory for creating cross

platform interfaces of the API client is moved from the static method

FacilitatedPaymentsApiClient::Create() in the core/browser/ directory to

a standalone function

CreateFacilitatedPaymentsApiClient(content::RenderFrameHost*) in the

content/browser/ directory.

entry.title: [test] Provide control of stack trace generation in tests
entry.content:
Collecting and emitting stack traces is not free. Tests that run in

debug configurations may time out solely due to this cost. There are

many cases in which stacks traces may never be visible to the developer.

One such case is in a death test's child proc: the child process is

expected to crash, so any stack traces generated for this are expected

and hidden.



In https://crrev.com/1246434 we suppressed the generation and printing

of stack traces in CHECK/LOG(FATAL)/etc messages in death tests. In

https://crrev.com/1272204 we replaced this with a change to `StackTrace`

itself to suppress output in any case in death tests. In this change, we

go one step further as follows:



By default, `base::debug::StackTrace` will no longer collect a trace in

a death test, and printing an empty stack trace will no longer do any

processing. Tests that require a stack trace in a death test may use

base::debug::OverrideStackTraceOutputForTesting to force-enable

generation and output of traces in death tests. Additionally, some

non-death tests may also result in the generation and emission of stack

traces that will never be seen (e.g., those that use

`EXPECT_FATAL_FAILURE`). These tests can use the same test helper to

suppress the generation and output of stack traces in non-death tests.

entry.title: [Viz] Allow GL_ARB_texture_rectangle extension in TestContextProvider
entry.content:
Production code invoked within the context of Blink unittests calls

ClientSharedImage::GetTextureTarget(BufferUsage). This function in turn

calls ClientSharedImage::GetTextureTarget(BufferUsage, BufferFormat),

which checks whether the pair is in

SharedImageCapabilities::texture_target_exception_list to determine

whether to return the platform-specific texture target. This list is

left empty within the context of these tests, meaning that GL_TEXTURE_2D

will always be returned.



An upcoming change to use ClientSharedImage::GetTextureTarget() will

result in the platform-specific texture target actually being returned

on Mac within the context of these tests (as is conceptually correct for

SharedImages with WebGPU usage). This is GL_TEXTURE_RECTANGLE_ARB by

default. This change results in these tests creating textures with this

target, which requires the GL_ARB_texture_rectangle extension. This CL

adds the extension to viz::TestContextProvider, which is the context

provider that these tests use.



Bug: 41494843

entry.title: storage: let AbstractFileEnumerator propagate errors
entry.content:
An AbstractFileEnumerator iterates through a directory's files but does

not propagate any error returned by the file system. This commit is the

first step towards fixing that.



More discussion / motivation is at b/329523214



For ChromeOS, this fixes b/328698363 "Fusebox+ODFS doesn't show re-auth

prompt".



In the changes to the LocalFileUtil::LocalFileEnumerator constructor

implementation, the file_enum_ constructor call went from 3 to 6

arguments. The 4th (empty string) and 5th (MATCH_ONLY) are now explicit,

but are the same as what the 3-arg constructor would implicitly use. The

important change is in the 6th and final argument, from an implicit

IGNORE_ERRORS to an explicit STOP_ENUMERATION policy.
